newsitem.title: USA: CSCE coffee ends near lows on spec liquidation.
newsitem.headline: CSCE coffee ends near lows on spec liquidation.

text.p: CSCE coffee prices ended weaker and just above intraday lows Monday, hurt by a late-session bout of speculative liquidation, market sources said.
In what was mainly an uneventful trading day, arabica prices drifted in negative territory from the opening bell.

Light selling by day traders held the market a notch below unchanged for most of the session, but disappointment over December's failure to carve out fresh upside territory inspired a swift round of speculative selling ahead of the close.

Most-active December briefly dipped below chart support at 111.00 cents a lb, touching a low of 110.80, before snapping back by the close. December closed down 1.70 at 111.20, while spot September slumped 2.10 to 122.50.

Traders said today's weaker settlement could signal a return to December's recent low of 108 cents. But most were reluctant to read much into today's session, noting the day's light volume of 4,034 lots.
"I think everyone is taking a breather from last week," said one trader. "A lot of people went home long on Friday, but everyone just bailed out on the opening."
Traders said tonight's certified stock data would likely show a modest change on the week, but most doubted the numbers would have a broad impact on prices.
Dealers also shrugged off talk of delays in Colombian coffe exports due to trucker protests and guerrilla attacks.
"No one seems to be overly concerned," the trader said. "I think the reaction by the market says it all."
